rudis+@cs.cmu.edu (Rujith S DeSilva) writes:

>In article <1su76e$5k7@fnnews.fnal.gov> newman@pokey.fnal.gov (Mark Newman)
>writes:
>>[Description of the problem removed for brevity.]

>I can think of a simpler method: the waiter supplies them with three identical
>pieces of paper, three identical pens, and a hat.  Each writes a `1' on his
>piece of paper, if he paid for the meal, else `0,' and puts it in the hat.
>The waiter then takes the three pieces of paper, and adds the numbers written
>on them.  If the waiter says the sum is 0, then a government agency paid for
>the meal; if he says the sum is 1, then one of the diners paid, and if he says
>2 or 3, then the restaurant was trying to rip-off the diners.

But it still requires that the waiter be trusted to give the total
correctly.  And if the waiter works for the government, then he/she
might answer 1 regardless of the actual answer, so as to shift the
blame.  Rather it seems that the cryptographers must do the inspection
themselves.
